@node ADD "Main / Add"

        Will add a new Newsgroup.  The cursor will go active in a
        string gadget where you can enter the group name you wish
        to convert.  (Ie.  comp.sys.amiga.misc).

        When  you  hit the 'return' key, you'll be prompted for a
        Fidonet TAGNAME.  Just chose one adequatly and type it in
        (Ie.  CSA_MISC).
@endnode
@node REMOVE "Main / Remove"

        Will remove a previously entered Newsgroup.
@endnode
@node FIDOTAG "Main / Fidonet TAGNAME"

        The   correspondent  Usenet  Newsgroup's  articles  will  be
        converted to messages of this Echomail area.
@endnode
@node HIDE_SIGS "Main / Hide Signatures"

        When  this flag is ON, UUCP2Fido will atempt to hide that
        huge  signatures  from  the  Usenet articles as these are
        being converted.

        WARNING:   I  can't  say  this is safe to use.  UUCP2Fido
        knows  that  the  start of a signature begins when a line
        has  '--'  or  '---'.  Use at your own risk but the worse
        that can happen is the signature be included.

        * As far as I know, there are no standard specifications
          about the start of a signature in a message body.
@endnode
@node HEADER_INFO "Main / Header Information Window"

        The  "All Lines" and "None" buttons are mutual exclusive.
        They  tell if the article  headers will or not be totally
        gated to Fidonet.

        If you don't use these buttons, you may tell which header
        lines  will  be shown in the Fidonet messages by clicking
        the appropriate buttons.

        You  may  apply  different  header  preferences  for each
        Newsgroup.

        Exemplification header:

            Path: etcelso
            From: etcelso@zeus.ua.pt (Celso Martinho)
            Newsgroups: local.tests
            Subject: Hi!
            Distribution: world
            Message-ID: <etcelso.02kf@zeus.ua.pt>
            Date: 2 Sep 92 16:14:41 GMT
            Organization: Not an Organization
@endnode
@node ORIGIN_LINE "Main / Origin Line"

        For  each  Fidonet EchoMail area you can enter a diferent
        Origin  Line  that  will  be  included with the converted
        Fidonet messages.
@endnode
@node INBOUND "Main / InBound Directory"

        The directory where @{"PKTGen" link "Monalisa:Documentation/Programs/PKTgen/main"} will store the converted PKTs.
        This is usually Mail:InBound/.  Your system's mailer (Ie.
        a  BBS  mailer) will then toss the PKTs are propagate the
        messages to the other systems you wish to feed.
@endnode
@node LOG_FILE "Main / Log File"

        This   is   the  file  where  UUCP2Fido  will  write  log
        information.   It  is advisable that you delete this file
        regurarly  as  it may get too big.  Optionaly you can use
        NIL:  if you don't want any log file.
@endnode
@node WORK_DIR "Main / Work Directory"

        This  is  the directory where all the work is going to be
        done.   Here is where UUCP2Fido will copy the batch files
        to,  decompress them, toss them and convert them to Fido.
        If  you  have a reasonable amount of free RAM, I strongly
        advise  you  to  use  T:   or  any  other RAM:  directory
        because  it  will strongly increase the convertion speed.
        Low  memory systems can use the disk and wait a bit more.
        Depending on the amount of batch files regularly found in
        UUSPOOL:, you can see what is the best option for you.
@endnode
@node GATEWAY_SYS "Main / Gateway System"

        Here  you  define  a  fake system.  Actually, no one will
        ever  call  you  with  this name.  Your UUCP package will
        create  the  bacthes  in  UUSPOOL:  for this ghost system
        with   the  conferences  you  wish.   When  UUCP2Fido  is
        executed,  it  will remove the packets from UUSPOOL:, and
        convert  everything  on  them  to Fidonet technology.  If
        you're  using  AmigaUUCP,  you  only  have  to  edit  the
        UULIB:Sys  file  and decide what groups you wish to gate.
        Read  UUMAN:Sys for more details.  A possible GATEWAY SYS
        name could be "monalisa" and UULIB:Sys could have a entry
        like:

        monalisa:comp.sys.amiga.misc,comp.sys.amiga.datacomm

        You will also need to add this system to your UULIB:L.sys
        so that AmigaUUCP thinks that your Gateway exists.

        Example:

        monalisa Any SER: 2400 ATDP0 ogin: uucp sword: uucp

        If  you're using Fido2UUCP as well, don't forget that the
        Gateway  names  must  match.   Otherwise,  you may create
        feedback problems.
@endnode
@node FROM_ADDRESS "Main / From Address"

        Converted  Fidonet packets will have this origin address.
        You  may  write here is your system's Fido address or the
        Fido  address  that  you  use  to  gate messages from the
        Fidonet  to  the Internet/Usenet in which case you should
        check your Fido2UUCP configuration.
@endnode
@node DECOMPRESSOR "Main / Decompressor"

        Later  versions  of  RNews support compressors other than
        'compress'.  Match this field with the compressor used by
        your  UUCP  package  (full path and filename).  If you're
        using  "compress"  (the  default for most systems), don't
        forget to turn the @{"ADD Z EXTENSION" link ADD_Z_EXT} flag ON.
@endnode
@node ADD_Z_EXT "Main / Add .Z Extension"

        Files   packed   with  'compress'  usually  have  the  .Z
        extension.   Turning  this  flag  ON  will make UUCP2Fido
        aware of this.  Of course this is useless if you're using
        another  compressor like 'lha' or 'gzip'.

        Also,  if  this  flag is ON, UUCP2Fido will not atempt to
        delete  the  uncompressed  files because the 'uncompress'
        command already does this.
@endnode
@node MAXMSGSIZE "Main / Maximum Message Size"

        Some  old  mailers don't support big Fidonet messages and
        may  reject  or  loose such.  You you are feeding systems
        like  this, you may want to set a limit for your messages
        in  bytes.   UUCP2Fido  will  divide messages bigger than
        this  limit  into two or more messages so that they don't
        exceed  your limit.  A good example is "Squish" very used
        in  the  MS-DOS  based  platforms.   It will tipicaly not
        accept messages bigger than 16K.

        Set this field to 0 if you don't want any article limits.

        Also  give  something  like  a 200 byte tolerance to this
        field.   This  is  because  some  control  information is
        appended  and  to make sure that sentences are not cut in
        the middle.
@endnode
@node PKTGEN_FLAGS "Main / PKTGen Flags"

        You  may  enter PKTGen flags here.  These will be used in
        UUCP2Fido   generated   packets.    If   you   are  using
        Excelsior's BBS mailer, XMail (till V1.21), you will need
        to  use  the MSGPRIVATE flag here, otherwise, packets are
        going to you Mail:Bad/ directory (dont ask me why).
@endnode
@node ADDFIDOACCEPT "E-Mail / Add Fido Acceptable"

        Will  add  an  entry  to  the  Fidonet "Acceptable" list.
        Wildcards  are  accepted.  Fidonet addresses can have the
        3D  or  4D format.  This list of systems will have access
        to  the  E-Mail  services  unless  denied  in the Fidonet
        "Rejectable"   list.    Examples  are  *:*/*.*,  2:*/*.*,
        2:361/*, etc...

        Pay atention to entries like "*:*/*.*".  This will reject
        the address 1:2/345 and accept the address 1:2/345.6.  If
        you want to give access to everyone, you'll have to write
        and  entry  like "*:*/*".  To understand Wilcards better,
        imagine  you're  in  CLI  and you type "dir #?.#?".  This
        will  only show  you files that have a "." in their name.
        If you type "dir #?", you'll get everything.
@endnode
@node REMFIDOACCEPT "E-Mail / Remove Fido Acceptable"

        Will  remove  a  previsouly entered and selected address.
        See @{"Add Fido Acceptable" link ADDFIDOACCEPT} for more details.
@endnode
@node ADDFIDOREJECT "E-Mail / Add Fido Rejectable"

        Will  add  an  entry  to  the  Fidonet "Rejectable" list.
        Wilcards are accepted.  Fidonet addresses can have the 3D
        or  4D  format.   This  is the list of systems who access
        will  be denied from the "Acceptable" list.  Systems that
        aren't in the "Acceptable" list don't have any efect here
        because  they aren't even being accept for the beggining.
        The  "Acceptable" list has priority over the "Rejectable"
        list.
@endnode
@node REMFIDOREJECT "E-Mail / Add Fido Rejectable"

        Will  remove  a  previsouly entered and selected address.
        See @{"Add Fido Rejectable" link ADDFIDOREJECT} for more details.
@endnode
@node ADDINETACCEPT "E-Mail / Add Internet Acceptable"

        Works  much like the Fidonet lists.  If will decide which
        Internet  systems  may use your gateway to send E-Mail to
        the Fidonet.

        See @{"Add Fido Acceptable" link ADDFIDOACCEPT} for more details.
@endnode
@node REMINETACCEPT "E-Mail / Rem Internet Acceptable"

        Will   remove   a   selected  entry  from  your  Internet
        Acceptable list.
@endnode
@node ADDINETREJECT "E-Mail / Add Internet Rejectable"

        Works  much like the Fidonet lists.  It will decide which
        system  may  NOT  use  your gateway to send E-Mail to the
        Fidonet.

        See @{"Add Fido Rejectable" link ADDFIDOREJECT} for more details.
@endnode
@node REMINETREJECT "E-Mail / Rem Internet Rejectable"

        Will   remove   a   selected  entry  from  your  Internet
        Rejectable list.
@endnode
@node REPBADMAIL "E-Mail / Reply to Bad Mail Flag"

        If  this  flag  is  set, UUCP2Fido will warn unauthorized
        systems  or  authorized  systems  that  didn't follow the
        standards about their attempt to use the gateway.
@endnode
@node REPMESG "E-Mail / Reply Message File"

        This  message  will be sent to users who tried to use the
        gateway  improperly.   The  @{"Reply Bad Mail" link REPBADMAIL} flag must be
        set.
@endnode
@node EMAIL_NOTES "E-Mail / Notes about E-Mail Gating"

        If  you are going to gate E-Mail to Netmail, don't forget
        to  edit  the  file  UULIB:Domain  and  add the following
        entries to it:

        *.@{"FUUN" link FUUN}                MF UU   @{"FUUN" link FUUN}
        *.@{"FUUN" link FUUN}.your.domain    MF UU   @{"FUUN" link FUUN}

        Where  FUUN is the Fake UUCP System Name is the site used
        to  gate  your  Usenet  articles  to Fidonet messages and
        vice-versa.
@endnode
@node FUUN "Fake UUCP System Name"

        The  Fake  UUCP System Name is the site used to gate your
        Usenet articles to Fidonet messages and vice-versa.
@endnode
@node HELP_KEY "General / The HELP key"

        Pressing  the  HELP  key will cause UUCP2Fido to show you
        UUCP2Fido documentation in AmigaGuide format.
@endnode
